Q: How can I achieve a gradient effect using CSS? A: <p>The key to this design wasn't just the color, but managing the stacking order with CSS. The goal was for the decorative waves to be visible at the edges, but to magically disappear behind the search bar so the text remained legible.</p>
<p>We achieved this using <code>SVG and masks</code>, and the <code>z-index</code> property to distinguish the layers as needed. To understand it, imagine the browser isn't a flat screen, but a table where we stack sheets of paper:</p>
<p>The &quot;Layered Building&quot; Structure
The Terrain <code>(#sa-filtro-container)</code>: By assigning a <code>z-index</code>, we define what's called a stacking context. It's like defining the plot of land for a building; from here, we can decide what goes on each floor within this container.</p>
<p>The Basement <code>(.sa-bg)</code>: We assign it a <code>z-index of 0</code>. This sends the gradient and waves to the very bottom. It's the base decoration that fills the gaps.</p>
<p>The First Floor <code>(.sa-card)</code>: This is the box that contains the search bar. By setting its <code>z-index to 1</code>, we raise it above the waves. Since this box has a solid background color (the cream tone), it acts as a &quot;lid&quot; that hides the waves passing underneath, leaving the text area clean and professional.</p>
<p>The Golden Rule
It's crucial to remember that <code>z-index</code> doesn't work alone. For the browser to understand that it should &quot;raise&quot; an element, it must have a defined position property (such as relative, absolute, or fixed). Without a declared position, the browser ignores the floors and leaves everything on the ground.</p>
<p>Here's an example.</p>
<pre><code>type here
</code></pre>
<p><div class="snippet" data-lang="js" data-hide="false" data-console="true" data-babel="false" data-babel-preset-react="false" data-babel-preset-ts="false">
<div class="snippet-code">
<pre class="snippet-code-css lang-css prettyprint-override"><code>/* 1. Mantenemos tu contenedor exterior con el degradado azul de fondo */
#sa-filtro-container {
    position: relative;
    max-width: 1100px;
    margin: 40px auto;
    padding: 40px;
    border-radius: 32px;
    overflow: hidden;
    background: radial-gradient(circle at center, #0b6fd1 0%, #4db2f5 100%);
    box-shadow: 0 30px 60px rgba(0,0,0,.25);
}

/* 2. CAPA DE DEGRADADO (ONDAS): Se queda igual, pero aseguramos su posición */
.sa-bg {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    z-index: 0; /* Al fondo del todo */
    pointer-events: none;
}

.sa-bg::before, .sa-bg::after {
    content: "";
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.55);
    -webkit-mask-repeat: no-repeat;
    mask-repeat: no-repeat;
}

.sa-bg::before {
    -webkit-mask-image: url("data:image/svg+xml;utf8,&lt;svg xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg' viewBox='0 0 300 300'&gt;&lt;path d='M0 0 C50 100,100 0,150 150 C200 300,250 150,300 300 L300 0 Z' fill='white'/&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;");
    -webkit-mask-position: top right;
    -webkit-mask-size: 50vmin;
}

.sa-bg::after {
    -webkit-mask-image: url("data:image/svg+xml;utf8,&lt;svg xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg' viewBox='0 0 300 300'&gt;&lt;path d='M300 300 C240 260 180 320 120 280 C60 240 100 180 40 140 C0 100 40 40 0 0 L0 300 Z' fill='white'/&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;");
    -webkit-mask-position: bottom left;
    -webkit-mask-size: 40vmin;
}

/* 3. LA CAJA DEL FORMULARIO: Aquí aplicamos el color uniforme solicitado */
.sa-card {
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1; /* Esto la pone por ENCIMA de las ondas de .sa-bg */

    /* CAMBIO CLAVE: Color azul sólido uniforme para que no se vea el degradado debajo */
    background: #3b78db; 

    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    padding: 40px;
    box-shadow: 0 18px 40px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.25);
}

/* 4. Mantenemos el resto de tus estilos intactos (textos, botones e inputs) */
#sa-filtro-container h3 {
    margin: 0 0 15px;
    font-size: 40px;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: #fff;
}

#sa-filtro-container p {
    margin: 0 0 35px;
    font-size: 20px;
    color: rgba(255, 255, 255, .9);
}

.sa-form {
    display: flex;
    align-items: stretch;
    gap: 20px;
}

.sa-input {
    flex: 1;
    height: 64px;
    padding: 0 24px;
    font-size: 20px;
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
    border: none;
    outline: none;
    color: #555;
    background: #fff; /* Aseguramos que el input sea blanco */
}

.sa-button {
    height: 64px;
    padding: 0 32px;
    background: #2b5fa8; /* Un azul un poco más oscuro para que contraste con el fondo de la caja */
    color: #fff;
    border: none;
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
    font-size: 22px;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    cursor: pointer;
}

#sa-resultado {
    margin-top: 45px;
}

#sa-resultado p {
    font-size: 38px;
    color: rgba(255, 255, 255, .85);
}

/* RESPONSIVE */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
    .sa-form { flex-direction: column; }
    .sa-button { width: 100%; }
}</code></pre>
<pre class="snippet-code-html lang-html prettyprint-override"><code>&lt;div id="sa-filtro-container"&gt;
        &lt;div class="sa-bg"&gt; &lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;div class="sa-card"&gt;

            &lt;h3&gt;Encuentra Elementos para transportar&lt;/h3&gt;

            &lt;p&gt;Introduce los elementos que necesitas &lt;/p&gt;

            &lt;form id="sa-filtro-form" class="sa-form"&gt;
                &lt;input type="text" id="sa_alergenos_input" name="alergenos_input" placeholder="placeholder_text"
                    class="sa-input"&gt;

                &lt;button type="submit" id="sa-btn-aplicar-filtro" class="sa-button"&gt;
                    BUSCAR ELEMENTOS
                &lt;/button&gt;
            &lt;/form&gt;

            &lt;div id="sa-resultado"&gt;
                &lt;p&gt;Introduce elementos para completar el transporte.&lt;/p&gt;
            &lt;/div&gt;

        &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
</p>

Q: How can I set cookie in node js using express framework? A: <p>The order in which you use middleware in Express matters: middleware declared earlier will get called first, and if it can handle a request, any middleware declared later will not get called.</p>
<p>If <code>express.static</code> is handling the request, you need to move your middleware up:</p>
<pre class="lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>// need cookieParser middleware before we can do anything with cookies
app.use(express.cookieParser());

// set a cookie
app.use(function (req, res, next) {
  // check if client sent cookie
  var cookie = req.cookies.cookieName;
  if (cookie === undefined) {
    // no: set a new cookie
    var randomNumber=Math.random().toString();
    randomNumber=randomNumber.substring(2,randomNumber.length);
    res.cookie('cookieName',randomNumber, { maxAge: 900000, httpOnly: true });
    console.log('cookie created successfully');
  } else {
    // yes, cookie was already present 
    console.log('cookie exists', cookie);
  } 
  next(); // &lt;-- important!
});

// let static middleware do its job
app.use(express.static(__dirname + '/public'));
</code></pre>
<p>Also, middleware needs to <em>either</em> end a request (by sending back a response), or pass the request to the next middleware. In this case, I've done the latter by calling <code>next()</code> when the cookie has been set.</p>
<p><strong>Update</strong></p>
<p>As of now, the cookie parser is a separate npm package, so instead of using:</p>
<pre class="lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>app.use(express.cookieParser());
</code></pre>
<p>you need to install it separately using <code>npm i cookie-parser</code> and then use it as:</p>
<pre class="lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>const cookieParser = require('cookie-parser');
app.use(cookieParser());
</code></pre>
